  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Zephath",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Only here; the site is unknown. So far as situation goes, es-Sebaita, 25 m. N.N.E. of ‘Ain el-Ḳadîs (Kadesh), would be suitable; but it has no philological connexion with Zephath (Ṣephath). The Canaanite name of the city which was known to the Hebrews as Hormah is not likely to have survived.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "utterly destroyed",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] So the AV. and RV. render the verb, but RVm. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "devoted, lit",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ‘placed under the ban,’ ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ḥérem",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " RV. ‘devoted thing,’ AV. ‘accursed thing.’ Underlying the practice was the ancient principle of taboo; the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ḥérem",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as the Arabic meaning of the root shews, was something ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "separated",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " from common use, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "secluded",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", wholly made over to the deity and therefore inviolable. Hence in Arab. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ḥarâm",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " = ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "sanctuary",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the Moslem name of the temple area at Jerusalem; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ḥarîm",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " = ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the women’s chambers",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; in Aram. dialects the word is used in various forms of a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "sanctuary",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "tomb",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (Nabataean), ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "consecrated offerings",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (Palmyrene). Among the Moabites we have an account of the practice which reads almost like a passage in the O.T.; King Mesha ‘devoted’ 7000 Israelite prisoners to ‘Ashtar-Chemosh (Moab. Stone, lines 16–18). Among the Hebrews anything which might endanger the religious life of the community was put out of harm’s way by being ‘devoted’ to God, and whatever was thus placed under the ban had to be destroyed; e.g. the idolatrous Canaanites, or the idolatrous Israelite city, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 10:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 10:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " etc., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jdg 11:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " etc.; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 13:15-17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 27:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " f. Instances of the practice are recorded in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
